Pass this letter to the head of MOS-1, Petrov A.V.

The head of the third research group of the laboratory X-7, F.A. Gusev, is writing to you. To my great regret, me, my group and many other scientists in the scientific complex could not agree with comrade Lebedev. The reason for the big scandal are different approaches to studying the problem of the noosphere, and, as many have expressed, his ambitions are too irrational not to mention he suffers from superiority complex.

Almost all the scientists have agreed to preform a connection to the noosphere as soon as possible, but N.A. Lebedev was categorically opposed claiming that there is not enough power reserved at the moment and the experiment can get out of control with unpredictable consequences. He also responded extremely negatively and impulsively about the finished and approved calculations of the commission.

It is worth noting that for many years, major conflicts (including conflicts with senior officials) have occurred with him before. As an example, I can cite the case when Lebedev negatively spoke about the plan for constructing the main generators North to the Chernobyl NPP, and was against some experiments the purpose of which was any result at first, and its further study after that. Despite many successes, a valuable contribution to our development and other merits (a detailed explanation of the device number 62 principle), the central external group has decided to dismiss N.A. Lebedev and other members of his team.

List of the dismissed (as of March 9, 2006):

Lebedev N.A.;
Fedotov A.A.;
Shilov B.N.;
Drozdov A.V.;
Kalancha E.F. (at own request);
Suslov V.I. (at own request).

The generators location plan. This document is to be passed to N.L. Ivanov


In this document, two possible plans of the main generators' location are described, and you will have to choose one because the research department employees' opinions have divided. The development went under the direction of G.R. Petrov and A.E. Kutsenko.


The first option.

Designed by: G.R. Petrov.

Location: 1600 meters to the North of ChNPP.

Advantages:
1. Presence of a huge area within which the construction can be conducted;
2. A good opportunity of delivering building materials through the border of the nearest country;
3. The chance of trespassing by strangers is reduced to zero: emitters will be built on the way to the plant, and we're planning to place the Monocrystal and the Monolith soldiers at the NPP itself;
4. The soil is easy to process;
5. Safety: in case of an emergency situation, the NPP itself would not be significantly damaged;
6. Relatively small dimensions of the object - and, as a result, less materials to spend.

Disadvantages:
1. Huge energy costs of transferring energy: we will inevitably have to create a high-voltage powerline and several transformers of big sizes near the NPP;
2. Building huge objects is energetically unprofitable;
3. Small dimensions of the object - and, as a result, less power and, possibly, insufficient stability.

Facility power: 60 000 units.

Energy costs: 500 000 units.

Cost price: 1 000 000 units.

Stability: 7/10.

Ratio of potential damage caused by the worst accident possible: 6 000.


The second option.

Designed by: A.E. Kutsenko.

Location: at the NPP itself.

Advantages:
1. Opportunity of building objects with high power consumption;
2. Proximity to the power source compensates energy costs, thus creation of generators of bigger dimensions is possible;
3. High stability;
4. Direct surveillance ability;
5. A formal excuse to remove the construction area from satellite maps;
6. Building the generators in the shape of rectangle is more profitable energetically (rather than circle);
7. No need to build a main signal sending antenna, calibration of which is extremely hard.

Disadvantages:
1. High risk of harming the facility is case of an NPP assault;
2. Hard to build;
3. More building materials to spend.

Facility power: 600 000 units.

Energy costs: 3 500 000 units.

Cost price: 9 000 000 units.

Stability: 9/10.

Ratio of potential damage caused by the worst accident possible: 180 000.


As you can see, the projects differ - and you are responsible for the final choice. Keep in mind that we currently wield all the needed funds and resources to stick to either of the plans.
Sincerely, N.A. Pavlov
